    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="995"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d995">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163 M 56/358</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 6011</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-12">January 12,
                            1942</date>.<lb/>[Received August 26.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Embassy’s telegram to the
                    Department No. 1728 of November 1, 3 p.m. (1941),<note n="84" xml:id="d995fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> stating that representations had been made with respect
                    to damage inflicted by Japanese armed forces on the property of the American
                    Methodist Mission at various places in Fukien Province, China, I have the honor
                    to enclose, for the record, a translation of a communication from the Japanese
                    Foreign Office dated December 4, 1941,<note n="84" xml:id="d995fn2">Not
                        printed.</note> requesting sketch maps showing the exact locations of the
                    damaged properties. War broke out between the United States and Japan before the
                    Embassy could take action in the matter.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph C. Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
